ness performance.\n* **Naked Short Positions & Stabilization:** The underwriters warn that a "naked short position" is more likely to be created if there is concern about downward pressure on the stock price post-pricing. To counter this, underwriters may engage in price stabilization activities (bidding for and purchasing shares in the open market) to artificially maintain or raise the stock price, though they are not obligated to do so.\n* **General Market Factors:** The stock price will be subject to wide fluctuations based on financial conditions, technological innovations, regulatory changes, competitor announcements, brand reputation, and broader macroeconomic conditions.\n\n### 3. Liquidity, Lock-Ups, & Future Share Sales\nThe prospectus details the mechanics of share liquidity, highlighting the tension between restricted pre-IPO shares and future public market availability:\n* **Restricted Securities & Lock-Ups:** All Class A and Class B shares issued prior to the IPO (including those held by Musk and existing investors) are deemed "restricted securities" under Rule 144. They are subject to contractual lock-up agreements, meaning only a limited number of shares will be available for sale immediately following the offering.\n* **Rule 144 Availability:** Approximately [redacted] shares will generally become available for resale under Rule 144 starting **90 days after the offering**, subject to the expiration or waiver of lock-up restrictions.\n* **Registration Rights:** Parties to the Investors’ Rights Agreement have the right to require the company to register shares under the Securities Act. Once registered, these shares become freely tradable without Rule 144 limitations.\n* **Market Overhang Risk:** The eventual lapse of these restrictions and the subsequent flooding of the public market with shares (or the perception of it) could adversely affect the prevailing market price and hinder the company\'s ability to raise equity-related capital in the future.\n\n### 4. Additional Ownership & Equity Risk Factors\n* **"Controlled Company" Status:** Following the IPO, Elon Musk\'s substantial beneficial ownership will classify the company as a "controlled company" under Nasdaq rules. This allows the company to rely on exemptions from certain corporate governance requirements (e.g., independent director nominations).\n* **Risk of Musk Reducing Ownership:** While Musk\'s current ownership aligns his economic incentives with the company\'s success, he is under no obligation to maintain his stake post-lock-up. If he sells a substantial portion of his shares, he may lose the incentive to assist in the company\'s success, which would adversely affect future prospects.\n* **Dilution & Capital Raises:** If the company raises additional capital via equity or convertible debt, existing shareholders could suffer significant dilution. Furthermore, new equity securities could carry rights, preferences, and privileges superior to those of Class A common stockholders.\n* **Long-Term vs. Short-Term Profitability:** The company warns that it will prioritize long-term growth over near-term financial performance. This strategy, combined with heavy capital expenditures in novel/untested technologies, could result in periods of reduced profitability or increased losses, which could negatively impact the stock price.',
