2026-06-09 21:31:34,964 DEBUG Run complete: AgentResult(
    final_answer='## SpaceX 2026 Stock Split: Underwriting/Market-Structure Rationales and Historical Per-Share Treatment\n\n### 1. Split Mechanics\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026) discloses a **five-for-one (5:1) forward stock split** of all authorized, issued, and outstanding shares of Class A, Class B, and Class C Common Stock, effective **May 4, 2026** — approximately two weeks before the S-1 filing date. This followed an earlier **10-for-1 split in 2022**, meaning the cumulative split adjustment from pre-2022 to the IPO is 50:1.\n\nThe filing\'s exact language from Note 1 states:\n\n> *"On May 4, 2026, the Company effected a five-for-one forward stock split of its authorized, issued, and outstanding shares of Class A, Class B, and Class C Common Stock (\'2026 Stock Split\'). The conversion rate of SpaceX Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock was proportionately adjusted to factor in the 2026 Stock Split. All share and per share information has been retroactively adjusted to reflect the 2026 Stock Split for all periods presented."*\n\n---\n\n### 2. Typical Underwriting and Market-Structure Rationales\n\n**The filing does not explicitly state a business rationale for the 2026 stock split.** Neither Note 1, Note 13, the Description of Capital Stock, nor the Underwriting section contains a sentence explaining *why* the split was executed. However, the filing\'s structure and disclosures strongly support the following standard rationales:\n\n#### a) Retail Investor Accessibility\nThe S-1 explicitly emphasizes retail access as a core IPO design feature:\n- Shares will be offered to retail investors at the same IPO price and time as institutional investors through **Charles Schwab, Fidelity, Robinhood, SoFi Securities, and E*TRADE** (via Morgan Stanley).\n- The filing warns that high retail interest may increase price volatility.\n\nA 5:1 split reduces the nominal per-share price, making whole-share purchases more accessible to retail investors on these platforms — many of which historically did not support fractional shares or have minimum-increment constraints. This is particularly relevant given the implied IPO price range of approximately **$82.50–$112.50 per share** (derived from the fee table\'s proposed maximum aggregate offering prices of ~$5.5B–$7.5B divided by the 66,666,670 shares being registered). Without the split, the nominal price would have been approximately **$412–$562 per share**, a level that creates friction for retail order entry and lot-size conventions.\n\n#### b) IPO Pricing and Syndicate Flexibility\nA lower nominal share price gives the lead underwriters (Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, BofA, Citigroup, J.P. Morgan) greater granularity in:\n- **Book-building**: More price points at which to gauge demand.\n- **Stabilization**: Morgan Stanley, as stabilization agent, can execute smaller-dollar open-market purchases to support the post-IPO price.\n- **Over-allotment management**: The 30-day greensheet option is more easily managed with a lower per-share price.\n\n#### c) Options and Derivatives Market Structure\nListed options on U.S. equities are standardized in 100-share lots. At ~$500/share, a single options contract would represent ~$50,000 of notional value — far too large for most market participants. At ~$100/share, a contract represents ~$10,000, which is the standard notional range for liquid single-stock options markets. The split thus facilitates the development of a liquid listed derivatives market post-IPO.\n\n#### d) Employee Equity Compensation Granularity\nWith a larger share count at a lower price, the company can make more granular equity grants (RSUs, options) to employees, allowing finer calibration of award values — particularly important given the filing\'s disclosure of ~598 million share-based compensation awards outstanding (post-split adjusted).\n\n#### e) Alignment with Multi-Class Capital Structure\nThe split was executed in conjunction with the creation of the new multi-class structure (Class A with 1 vote/share, Class B with 10 votes/share, Class C with no voting rights) and the xAI/X mergers. The split established the authorized share counts needed for the post-IPO capitalization:\n- **Class A**: 36,132,150,000 authorized shares\n- **Class B**: 6,125,000,000 authorized shares\n- **Class C**: 10,000,000,000 authorized shares\n\n---\n\n### 3. How the Filing Reflects the Split in Historical Per-Share Data\n\nThe filing applies **full retroactive adjustment** to all historical per-share data. This is the standard accounting treatment under ASC 260 (Earnings Per Share) for stock splits. Specifically:\n\n#### a) Retroactive Adjustment Across All Periods\nAll share and per-share information for **all periods presented** in the financial statements has been retroactively adjusted. This means:\n- The weighted-average share counts used in EPS calculations for 2023, 2024, 2025, and Q1 2026 all reflect the post-split share count.\n- No "pre-split" per-share figures appear anywhere in the prospectus.\n\n#### b) Historical EPS (Post-Split Adjusted)\n\n| Period | Net Income (Loss) | Basic EPS | Diluted EPS | Basic Wtd-Avg Shares (M) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | $(4,276)M | $(1.27) | $(1.27) | 3,884 |\n| Q1 2025 | $(528)M | $(0.18) | $(0.18) | 2,875 |\n| FY 2025 | $(4,937)M | $(1.69) | $(1.69) | 2,926 |\n| FY 2024 | $791M | $0.01 | $0.00 | 2,848 |\n| FY 2023 | $(4,628)M | $(1.68) | $(1.68) | 2,759 |\n\nThese EPS figures are presented on a split-adjusted basis. Without the 5:1 adjustment, the basic weighted-average shares for FY 2025 would have been approximately 585 million (2,926M ÷ 5), and the basic EPS would have been approximately $(8.45) rather than $(1.69).\n\n#### c) Preferred Stock Conversion Rate Adjustment\nThe conversion rate of SpaceX Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock was proportionately adjusted: each preferred share became convertible into **50 shares** of common stock (reflecting the cumulative effect of the 2022 10:1 split and the 2026 5:1 split, i.e., 10 × 5 = 50).\n\n#### d) Pro Forma EPS Also Split-Adjusted\nThe unaudited pro forma EPS (which assumes conversion of all preferred stock into common) is also presented on a split-adjusted basis:\n- **Pro forma diluted shares**: 10,607 million (Q1 2026) and 9,649 million (FY 2025)\n- **Pro forma EPS**: $(0.41) for Q1 2026 and $(0.51) for FY 2025\n\n#### e) Common-Control Recast Interaction\nImportantly, the historical per-share data reflects **both** the retroactive stock split adjustment **and** the retrospective recast under common-control accounting to include xAI (merged February 2, 2026) and X Holdings (merged into xAI March 28, 2025) for all periods. The weighted-average share counts therefore include shares deemed issued to xAI and X holders at the applicable exchange ratios, multiplied by the 5:1 split factor. No period reflects standalone SpaceX operations exclusively.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\nThe 2026 stock split is a mechanical, pre-IPO capital-structure action with no explicitly stated rationale in the filing, but its purposes are evident from the IPO\'s design: enabling retail accessibility (a stated priority), facilitating orderly post-IPO trading and stabilization, and aligning the share count with the new multi-class structure. The filing reflects the split through comprehensive retroactive adjustment of all historical share counts, per-share metrics, and conversion ratios across every period presented, ensuring that investors see only split-adjusted figures throughout the prospectus.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
